    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\n`foldcolumn` shows the collapsed number of folds (when 1 < `fdc` < `foldlevel()`) on multiple columns.\n\nI might be misunderstanding what the numbers in `fdc` represent. Apologies if that's the case!\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. `nvim --clean -c 'set fdc=2'`\n2. Insert 4 lines\n3. Create 3 folds from each of the first 3 lines that all end on line 4: `:1,3norm zfGzo`\n\n<img width=\"584\" height=\"268\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/a167b27c-68fd-48a4-b5a2-1c6809bc9600\" />\n\n\n### Expected behavior\n\n`23` for line 4 in the fold column is confusing. Both line 3 and line 4 have a `foldlevel()` of 3.\n\nSomething more intuitive that I would expect: have last column of `fdc` act as the \"overflow\" indicator, so at most one digit appears per line:\n\n<img width=\"584\" height=\"268\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2af8336b-997a-4f65-9858-0a02f25f3d7a\" />\n\nHere `2` would be representing two instances of `foldsep` that were omitted (second and third fold). This would be a more familiar pattern, and it would be similar to the message overflow count of `ui2`.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.13.0-dev-544+gc7ea9c075a\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, 9.2\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux 7.0.9\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm 20251201-075747-d3b0fdad\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> 23 for line 4 in the fold column is confusing. Both line 3 and line 4 have a foldlevel() of 3.\n\nThe `-` on line 3 indicates that an open fold starts on line 3, the `2` indicates that it is contained in 2 additional folds. So both line 3 and line 4 indicate a foldlevel of 3.\n\nYour expected behavior obfuscates the fact that line 3 is also contained in the folds starting on line 1 and 2.",
